attributes.title: Fills And Grooves Against The Dotted 8th Note Pulse

attributes.value: The six stroke roll is one of the 40 drum rudiments. This course will provide you with some speed and control exercises and also some practical drum-set applications.
The seven stroke roll is one of the 40 drum rudiments. This course will provide you with some practice pad exercises to help you develop speed and control, and also some drum-set applications.
The nine stroke roll is one of the 40 drum rudiments. This course will provide you with some practice pad exercises to help you develop speed and control, and also some drum-set applications.
The ten stroke roll is one of the 40 drum rudiments. This course will provide you with some speed and control exercises and also some practical drum-set applications.
The eleven stroke roll is one of the 40 drum rudiments. This course will provide you with some speed and control exercises and also some practical drum-set applications.
Aaron Edgar will teach you how play quintuplets in this course. He'll provide you with speed and control exercises, as well as some quintuplet beats and fills!
Aaron Edgar will teach you how play septuplets in this course. He'll provide you with speed and control exercises, as well as some septuplet beats and fills!

In this course, you'll be introduced to the concept of linear drumming. Issah Contractor will explain what linear drumming is and he'll also show you some different linear patterns, grooves, and fills!

Once you've completed the beginner linear drumming course, you can move on to this course! Issah Contractor will provide you with a some different linear patterns, some linear beats, and some linear drum fills. You can also apply these to a play-along track at the end of the course!

Peter Erskine will walk you through some unique practice exercises that will focus on creativity. He will cover topics like "The Comping Game," "Self Discovery Practice," and "Limitation vs. Imitation."
If you want to learn about ghost notes, this is the perfect course to start with! Jay Deachman will explain what ghost notes are, how to play them, and also how to add them to your beats and fills.

This Course is all about exploration and learning about styles of music and drumming you have probably never heard about, which is a great way to expand on your vocabulary and enhance your creativity. In it, Tosin will teach you how to play beats and fills for five styles of African music: Makossa, Soukous, High Life, Bikutsi, and Afrobeat.

Drum corps is a highly demanding style of snare drumming. With that in mind, John Wooton put together this eight-lesson Course for you, so you can learn how to properly develop your skills. This includes lessons on roll quality, developing your timing, speed, grids, the real rudiments of drumming, and how to play in an ensemble.

Being creative with your drum fills is fun and engaging, as well as a great way to increase your vocabulary, independence, and musicality on the kit. In this Course, Luke Holland will share some of the concepts he uses when developing his own unique fills so you too can become a very creative musician.

In this Course, Jeff Salem will teach you how to feel and play different 4/4 beats, fills, and solos, over the dotted eighth-note pulse. To do so, he'll show you how to develop your ability to play with a 4-over-3 feel, so you can easily move in and out of it and execute all your patterns over the dotted eighth-note pulse.

The rock beat formula was created with the intent of helping any beginner rock drummer get the most out of the beats they know how to play, with a few simple alterations. These include changing the lead hand pattern, the instruments on which such patterns are played, using ghost notes, and swinging the grooves.

The paradiddle sweep is one of Dennis Chambers' most recognizable showmanship techniques for soloing. In this Course, Dennis will teach you how to perform it by showing you how to develop the sweeping motion behind it and how to successfully move it around the kit.

In this Course you'll learn how to play the paradiddle-riddle-diddle: a variation of the paradiddle-diddle that features an extra set of double strokes. Besides being taught how to perform and develop this pattern, you'll also learn how to build your own voice on the kit with it and how to use it to enhance your playing, either as a beat or as a fill.

The Fastest Way To Get Faster is a 10-step routine that will help you rapidly improve your speed around the kit. You will need to practice hard, you will need to stick with it, and you might need to push yourself harder than usual - but it's been created to deliver results.

In this Course you're going to learn how to play grooves from five Porcupine Tree tunes, with help from the wizard that crafted them: Gavin Harrison. As a bonus, Gavin will also teach you a groove from a song he put together with 05Ric, besides providing you with a play-along to go with it.
